The paper focuses on developing a framework for automatically deriving GUI-based models from Android app execution traces, events, or source code. This involves techniques such as statistical language modeling, static and dynamic analyses, and interactive execution of the app on a real device. These techniques are commonly used in software engineering (cs.SE) and programming languages (cs.PL) research. Additionally, the paper emphasizes the importance of generating feasible and fully replayable scenarios reflecting natural user behavior or uncommon usages, which relates to human-computer interaction (cs.HC) and social computing (cs.SI) research. Finally, the paper evaluates the proposed framework using several open-source Android apps, which involves machine learning (cs.LG) techniques for model evaluation and validation.
